In the context of neural networks, parallelisation refers to the simultaneous execution of multiple sequential data processing operations. This means that the operations are performed on multiple data sets in a single pass, instead of one data set at a time.
This has the advantage of reducing the time required for processing a given data set. At optimal parallelisation, the processing time can be reduced by a factor proportional to the number of data sets being processed simultaneously.
To parallelise a neural network, you can use the Map Reduce system. This is a technique in which the neural network is divided into a series of Map tasks, each of which is responsible for processing a single data set, and a Reduce task which aggregates the results of multiple Map tasks.
It is important to note that parallelisation is often limited by computational power and memory resources, as well as by the structure and complexity of the neural network itself.
You can follow a simple steps for parallesing
1. Divide the neural network into multiple sub-layers, if possible.
2. Distribute the parallel components of the neural network across multiple cores, threads or processors.
